Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 4898 white wines in the dataset with 13 features(X, fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, density, sulphates, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, pH, alcohol and quality). The quality and X are int type and the rest are number. For have a good sense of quality, the variable could be ordered by factor variable with 7 levels.The most white wine are in quality 6 and the least in quality 9.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The total sulfur dioxide, free sulfur dioxide are my aimed features. The reason I choose the two variables is the effect of the sulfur in white wine. Does the form of sulfur dioxide impact the quality?

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

The density, residual sugar and pH may contribute to my investigation because the sulfate are affected by pH in the wine. The residual might impact the density.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes, I creat a new variable called free sulfur dioxide rate.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I change the data type of some variances to observe the distributions more convenient. Excepted the alcohol, the other features all has the outliers in a varying degrees. There are several unusual peaks in the distribution of citric acid.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

First, I guess the sulphates might impact the free sulfur dioxide rate. The result shows sulphates has no strong linear relationship with free sulfur dioxide rate which the correlation coefficient is only -0.022.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Yes, I discover the residual sugar is intensely correlated with density. It could be residual sugar own a large relative molecular mass compared the other chemical components in the wine. The sugar belongs to carbohydrates which generally have a huge relative molecular mass in chemistry.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The relationship between residual sugar and density because its correlation coefficient up to 0.84 which means a intense relation.

Reflection

From the analyze the white wine dataset, we could find some interesting phenomenons while ploting some conditional figures. Our interested features are free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide. We can discover the amount of sulfur dioxide doesn’t impact quality strongly whatever the total sulfur dioxide or free sulfur dioxide. However, the high quality wine is prone to have a high free sulfur dioxide rate and distributes around the mean value in either sulfur dioxide .
Considering the other features, according to the correlation coefficient matrix, we investigate the relation among density, residual sugar and alcohol. The three variances are related with each other strongly. Apart from that, The density also has a strong relation with total sulfur dioxide. For the powerful relation between residual sugar with density, We think the sugar has a large relative molecular mass compared to other composition in the wine. The same to total sulfur dioxide, the density increase while total sulfur dioxide adding. Then, We guess the free sulfur dioxide rate may related with sulphates. The result shows that we were wrong because of the correlation coefficient close to zero that signifies weak relation. Afterwards, we print the density diagram to view the distributions of free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide. The joint distribution map of the two variables is similar to the 3-D normal distribution. Finally, we check the boxplot of the free sulfur dioxide rate. During the analysis, the relation between different variables make us confused. The density connect to several variables and how the relations like among these variables doesn’t explore. The research isn’t fully investigating and it still has some questions to analyze.For example, whether the relation between alcohol and density is a coincide or something need to study.
